1072","Turvey, Bedfordshire, England":"Turvey, Bedfordshire, England","Radwell, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Turvy, Eng":"Turvey, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1094–":"1094–Overleden","1094–Male":"1094–Overleden","1096–Male":"1096–Overleden","1096–Female":"1096–Overleden","1120–1210":"1120–1210","1130–1197":"1130–1197","1132–Male":"1132–Overleden","1072–Male":"1072–Overleden","1072–Female":"1072–Overleden","Abt 1120":"circa 1120","1106":"1106","1210":"1210","1132":"1132","1197":"1197","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","about 1132":"circa 1132","1094":"1094","1072":"1072","Turvey, Bedfordshire, England":"Turvey, Bedfordshire, England","Radwell, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Turvy, Eng":"Turvey, Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1094–":"1094–Deceased","1094–Male":"1094–Deceased","1096–Male":"1096–Deceased","1096–Female":"1096–Deceased","1120–1210":"1120–1210","1130–1197":"1130–1197","1132–Male":"1132–Deceased","1072–Male":"1072–Deceased","1072–Female":"1072–Deceased","Abt 1120":"about 1120","1106":"1106","1210":"1210","1132":"1132","1197":"1197","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","about 1132":"about 1132","1094":"1094","1072":"1072","Turvey, Bedfordshire, England":"Turvey, Bedfordshire, England","Radwell, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Turvy, Eng":"Turvey, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mordaunt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>mordant</i> ‘biting, sarcastic’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Radwell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from either of the two places called Radwell (Beds, Herts), occasionally perhaps from Redwell Wood (Herts). The Radwells, both recorded as  <i>Radeuuelle</i> in 1086 (   Domesday Book  ), are named with Old English  <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ +  <i>welle</i> ‘spring, stream’.","2  English: locative name perhaps occasionally from Middle English  <i>rid(de) wold</i> (Old English  <i>(ge)ryd(d) weald</i>) ‘cleared woodland’, denoting someone who lived in or near an area of cleared woodland."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodwell","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of the three places called Rothwell (Lincolnshire, Northamptonshire, Yorkshire), from Old English <i>roth</i> ‘clearing’ + <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’.","habitational name from Radwell (Hertfordshire) or Radwell in Felmersham (Bedfordshire) and perhaps also from other places similarly named. The placenames derive from Old English <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + <i>wella</i> ‘spring, stream, well’."]},{"name":"Reddall","meanings":["English:  see  Radwell  ."]},{"name":"Domesday Book","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Bern</i>,  <i>Barn</i>. In the Midlands and East Anglia this is based on the Scandinavian personal name  <i>Biǫrn</i>, anglicized as  <i>Beorn</i>; in the south-west it is from Old English  <i>Beorn</i>; both names are from a word meaning ‘warrior’. Some of the following surname bearers may alternatively belong with other senses below.","2  English: status name from Middle English  <i>barn</i> (Old Scandinavian  <i>barn</i>) ‘child’. This term is found in   Domesday Book   as a byname for men of the upper classes; it might also have had the meaning ‘young man of a prominent family’, like Middle English  <i>child</i> (  see  Child  ).","3  English: locative name, nickname for residence near or employment at a barn, Middle English  <i>bern</i> (Old English  <i>bere-ærn</i>).  See also  Barnes  . Some of the post-medieval bearers may alternatively belong with (1) or (2)."]},{"name":"Reddell","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Radwell (Hertfordshire) or Radwell in Felmersham (Bedfordshire), both recorded as <i>Radeuuelle</i> in 1086, and perhaps also from other places similarly named. The placenames derive from Old English <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + <i>wella</i> ‘spring, stream, well’.","perhaps occasionally a topographic name from Middle English <i>rid(de) wold</i> (Old English <i>(ge)ryd(d)</i> ‘cleared’ + <i>weald</i> ‘woodland, high woodland subsequently cleared’) denoting someone who lived in or near an area of cleared woodland."]}]},{"name":"Osbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It is not now common, but in the earlier 20th century it enjoyed a modest vogue in Britain, being borne for example by the cartoonist  Osbert Lancaster  (  1908–86 ) and the writer  Osbert Sitwell  (  1892–1969 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":2,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":12,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Osbert Mordaunt of Radwell was born in 1094, in Turvey, Bedfordshire, England, his father, Robert of St Giles, was 23 and his mother, Mrs Robert of St Giles, was 23. He had at least 3 sons with Mrs Osbert Mordaunt. He died in Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1094–":"1094–Surnud","1094–Male":"1094–Surnud","1096–Male":"1096–Surnud","1096–Female":"1096–Surnud","1120–1210":"1120–1210","1130–1197":"1130–1197","1132–Male":"1132–Surnud","1072–Male":"1072–Surnud","1072–Female":"1072–Surnud","Abt 1120":"umbes 1120","1106":"1106","1210":"1210","1132":"1132","1197":"1197","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","about 1132":"umbes 1132","1094":"1094","1072":"1072","Turvey, Bedfordshire, England":"Turvey, Bedfordshire, England","Radwell, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Turvy, Eng":"Turvey, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1094–":"1094–Kuollut","1094–Male":"1094–Kuollut","1096–Male":"1096–Kuollut","1096–Female":"1096–Kuollut","1120–1210":"1120–1210","1130–1197":"1130–1197","1132–Male":"1132–Kuollut","1072–Male":"1072–Kuoll